# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: backspin
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:backspin/atp-250-tournaments-p01] The **ATP 250** tournaments are the lowest tier of annual men's tennis tournaments on the main ATP Tour, after the four Grand Slam tournaments, ATP Finals, ATP 1000 tournaments, and ATP 500 tournaments.
[src:backspin/atp-250-tournaments-p01] The winners of each tournament are awarded 250 ranking points—which accounts for the name of the series.
[src:backspin/atp-250-tournaments-p01] As of 2025, the series included 30 tournaments after the retirement of four tournaments (Atlanta, Córdoba, Metz and Marseille), the downgrade of two in 2025 (Estoril for a year, and Newport) and the upgrade of three tournaments to the 500 level (Dallas, Doha and Munich).
[src:backspin/atp-250-tournaments-p01] This is a significant reduction from the 50+ World Series tournaments in the 1990s.
[src:backspin/atp-250-tournaments-p01] Draws usually consist of 28 for singles, with Brisbane International (32) and Winston-Salem Open (48) being the only exceptions.
[src:backspin/atp-250-tournaments-p01] Thomas Muster holds the record for most singles titles at 26, while Mike Bryan holds the record for most doubles titles won with 46.
[src:backspin/atp-250-tournaments-p01] While the men's event was abolished, the women's event is still active.
[src:backspin/atp-500-tournaments] The **ATP 500 tournaments** (previously known as the *ATP World Tour 500* tournaments, *ATP International Series Gold*, and *ATP Championship Series*) are the fourth-highest tier of annual men's tennis tournaments, after the four Grand Slam tournaments, ATP Finals, and the ATP Masters 1000 events.
[src:backspin/atp-500-tournaments] The winners of each tournament are awarded 500 ranking points—which accounts for the name of the series.
[src:backspin/atp-500-tournaments] As of 2025, the series includes 16 tournaments, which have draws of 32 for singles (except for the Washington Open: 48) and 16 for doubles.
[src:backspin/atp-500-tournaments] Leading players must enter at least four 500 events, including at least one after the US Open; if they play fewer than four, or fail to play in one after the US Open they get a "zero" score towards their world ranking for each one short.
[src:backspin/atp-500-tournaments] Roger Federer has won the most ATP 500 singles titles (24), while Daniel Nestor has won the most doubles titles (20).
[src:backspin/atp-challenger-tour] The **ATP Challenger Tour** (known until the end of 2008 as the **ATP Challenger Series**) is a series of international men's professional tennis tournaments.
[src:backspin/atp-challenger-tour] It was founded in 1976 as a replacement for the ILTF Satellite Circuit (founded in 1971) as the second tier of tennis.
[src:backspin/atp-challenger-tour] The Challenger Tour events are the second-highest tier of tennis competition, behind the ATP Tour and ahead of the Men's World Tennis Tour tournaments.
[src:backspin/atp-challenger-tour] The ATP Challenger Tour is administered by the Association of Tennis Professionals (ATP).
[src:backspin/atp-challenger-tour] Players who succeed on the ATP Challenger Tour earn sufficient ranking points to enter the main or qualifying draws at ATP Tour tournaments.
[src:backspin/atp-challenger-tour] Players on the Challenger Tour are typically young players looking to advance their careers, those who fail to qualify for ATP events, or former ATP Tour players looking to return to the top tour.
[src:backspin/atp-challenger-tour] The first challenger events were held in 1978, with eighteen events taking place.
[src:backspin/atp-challenger-tour] Two were held on the week beginning January 8, one in Auckland and another in Hobart.
[src:backspin/atp-challenger-tour] The next events were held one at a time beginning June 18 and ending August 18 in the following U.S. locations, in order: Shreveport, Birmingham, Asheville, Raleigh, Hilton Head, Virginia Beach, Wall, Cape Cod, and Lancaster.
[src:backspin/atp-challenger-tour] Events continued after a one-month hiatus with two that begun on September 24 and 25, one in Tinton Falls, New Jersey, and in Lincoln, Nebraska, respectively.
[src:backspin/atp-challenger-tour] The following week saw one event played, in Salt Lake City, then two played simultaneously in Tel Aviv and San Ramon, California, then one played the following week in Pasadena.
[src:backspin/atp-challenger-tour] A final event was played a month later in Kyoto.
[src:backspin/atp-challenger-tour] In comparison, the 2008 schedule saw 178 events played in more than 40 countries.
[src:backspin/atp-challenger-tour] In efforts to further the progression of college and junior players into the professional tour, the ATP Challenger Tour has partnered with the Intercollegiate Tennis Association (ITA) and World Tennis to give players more opportunities on the professional tour.
[src:backspin/atp-challenger-tour] Those that finish in the top 10 of the end-of-year college rankings are now eligible for six wild cards into the main draw of Challenger events, and if they have finished their college education, they receive 8 of those wild cards.
[src:backspin/atp-challenger-tour] Those that finish in the 11 through 20 range of the collegiate rankings are eligible for six qualifying wild cards, with those who have completed their college education being eligible for eight wild cards.
[src:backspin/atp-challenger-tour] Much like the partnership with the ITA, the Challenger Tour also partnered with World Tennis.
[src:backspin/atp-challenger-tour] This partnership granted those with year-end rankings inside the top 10 in the world eligible for eight main draw Challenger Tour wildcards, and those who finished the year between 11 and 20 in the world receiving eight Challenger Tour qualifying wildcards.
[src:backspin/atp-challenger-tour] In 2022, during the most numerous season in the tour's history, the ATP Tour announced an overhaul of the tournaments system from 2023 season.
[src:backspin/atp-challenger-tour] Challenger 110 and Challenger 90 events were scrapped, Challenger 80 reduced to the Challenger 75 while the prize money requirements for it and Challenger 100 were increased.
[src:backspin/atp-challenger-tour] It also introduced the new highest category − Challenger 175 to be inaugurally held in the second week of Indian Wells, Rome and Madrid ATP Tour Masters 1000 events.
[src:backspin/atp-challenger-tour] Players have usually had success at the Futures tournaments of the Men's World Tennis Tour before competing in Challengers.
[src:backspin/atp-challenger-tour] Due to the lower level of points and money available at the Challenger level, most players in a Challenger have a world ranking of 100 to 500 for a $35K tournament and 50 to 250 for a $150K tournament.
[src:backspin/atp-challenger-tour] An exception happens during the second week of a Grand Slam tournament, when top-100 players who have already lost in the Slam try to take a wild card entry into a Challenger tournament beginning that second week.
[src:backspin/atp-challenger-tour] In February 2007, Tretorn became the official ball of the Challenger Series, and the sponsor of a new series consisting of those Challenger tournaments with prize money of $100,000 or more.
[src:backspin/atp-challenger-tour] They renewed the sponsorship with the ATP in 2010 and extended it until the end of 2011.
[src:backspin/atp-challenger-tour] The Tampere Open is the longest running ATP Challenger event.
[src:backspin/atp-cup] The **ATP Cup** was an international outdoor hard court men's tennis team tournament, which ran from 2020 to 2022.
[src:backspin/atp-cup] The tournament was played across one or three Australian cities over ten days in the lead up to the Australian Open, and featured teams from 12, 16 or 24 countries.
[src:backspin/atp-cup] The event was the first ATP team competition since the ATP World Team Cup, which was held in Düsseldorf from 1978 to 2012.
[src:backspin/atp-cup] On 2 July 2018, ATP director Chris Kermode announced that he had plans to organise a men's team tennis tournament in response to the Davis Cup changing their format six months earlier.
[src:backspin/atp-cup] The tournament at the time of the announcement had the name *World Team Cup*, taking from the previous World Team Cup that took place in Düsseldorf from 1978 to 2012.
[src:backspin/atp-cup] On 15 November, the ATP and Tennis Australia announced that the tournament would be known as the *ATP Cup*, with 24 teams playing at three cities in preparation for the Australian Open.
[src:backspin/atp-cup] Those cities would later be revealed to be Sydney, Brisbane and Perth; the new event would also result in the cancellation of the similar mixed-gender Hopman Cup tournament previously played in Perth (it would later be revived in 2023, relocated to Nice, France).
[src:backspin/atp-cup] The tournament took place in Sydney, Brisbane, and Perth, with Sydney the hosts of the quarter-finals onwards.
[src:backspin/atp-cup] In 2021, the tournament was deferred several weeks, and moved to Melbourne Park with 12 teams, due to the restrictions on domestic travel in Australia stemming from the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:backspin/atp-cup] The 2022 event would be held in Sydney with 16 teams as these restrictions were ongoing.
[src:backspin/atp-cup] Following the 2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine, the ITF barred Russia and Belarus from competing at the tournament.
[src:backspin/atp-cup] On 7 August 2022, amid an unsuccessful run hampered by low attendance and COVID-19-related issues, Tennis Australia announced that the ATP Cup would be replaced by a new mixed team event known as the United Cup beginning in 2023.
[src:backspin/atp-cup] The new event is a collaboration between Tennis Australia, the ATP, and the WTA, with players in the group stage also eligible to receive ATP and WTA rankings points.
[src:backspin/atp-cup] The teams that participated in the Cup were determined by the singles ranking of their best player.
[src:backspin/atp-cup] In the week after the US Open, 18 teams were announced, based on the best player singles ranking.
[src:backspin/atp-cup] For a country to qualify, it had to have at least three players with ATP ranking, and two of them with singles ranking.
[src:backspin/atp-cup] The next six teams were announced the week of the ATP Finals.
[src:backspin/atp-cup] If the host did not qualify on the first deadline of September, it would be awarded a wild card, leaving only five spots for the November deadline.
[src:backspin/atp-cup] The format saw 24 teams divided into six groups of four teams each.
[src:backspin/atp-cup] The teams faced in ties composed of two singles matches and one doubles match.
[src:backspin/atp-cup] 2 of each team opened the tie, then the No.1 of each team, and the doubles match closing the tie.
[src:backspin/atp-cup] The doubles match would be played regardless whether the tie is decided or not.
[src:backspin/atp-cup] The winner from each group was joined by the two best second placed teams in the quarterfinals of the tournament for three knock-out rounds, culminating in the champion being crowned.
[src:backspin/atp-cup] In 2020 ABC Bullion, a Pallion company, was awarded the rights to make the Cup.
[src:backspin/atp-cup] Sanders, a sister division within Pallion and took over 250 hours to produce.
[src:backspin/atp-finals] The **ATP Finals** is the season-ending championship of the ATP Tour.
[src:backspin/atp-finals] It is the most significant tennis event in the men's annual calendar after the four majors, as it features the top eight singles players and top eight doubles teams based on their results throughout the season.
[src:backspin/atp-finals] The eighth spot is reserved, if needed, for a player or team who won a major in the current year and is ranked from ninth to twentieth.
[src:backspin/atp-finals] The tournament uses a unique format not seen in other ATP Tour events, where the singles players and doubles teams are separated into two groups of four, within which they each play three round-robin matches.
[src:backspin/atp-finals] After the round-robin stage, the top two performers from each group play in knock-out semifinals and a final to determine the champion(s).
[src:backspin/atp-finals] The tournament was first held in 1970, shortly after the beginning of the Open Era.
[src:backspin/atp-finals] Novak Djokovic holds the record for the most singles titles with seven, while the doubles team of Peter Fleming and John McEnroe jointly hold the record for the most doubles titles with seven (which the pair won consecutively, 1978–1984).
[src:backspin/atp-finals] In the tournament's current format, the champion can earn a maximum of 1,500 ranking points, if they win the event after going undefeated in the round-robin stage.
[src:backspin/atp-finals] By winning the 2025 title, Sinner earned a record $5,071,000, the highest payout for an ATP tournament winner in tennis.
[src:backspin/atp-finals] The ATP Finals is the fifth iteration of a championship which began in 1970.
[src:backspin/atp-finals] It was originally known as the **Masters Grand Prix** and was part of the Grand Prix tennis circuit.
[src:backspin/atp-finals] The Masters was a year-end showpiece event between the best players on the men's tour; under the administration of the Men's International Professional Tennis Council (MIPTC) made up of ATP, ITF, and tournament representatives.
[src:backspin/atp-finals] During this era the Masters existed as a high prize money special year-end event, that existed outside the standard weekly points race.
[src:backspin/atp-finals] It ran alongside the competing WCT Finals from 1971 to 1989.
[src:backspin/atp-finals] In 1990, the Association of Tennis Professionals (ATP) took over the running of the men's tour and replaced the Masters with the "ATP Tour World Championships".
[src:backspin/atp-finals] World ranking points were now at stake, with an undefeated champion earning a maximum of 1500 points.
[src:backspin/atp-finals] The ITF, who continued to run the Grand Slam tournaments, created a rival year-end event known as the Grand Slam Cup, which was contested by the 16 players with the best records in the Grand Slam tournaments of the season (1990–99).
[src:backspin/atp-finals] In December 1999, the ATP and ITF agreed to discontinue the two separate events and create a new jointly owned event called the "Tennis Masters Cup".
[src:backspin/atp-finals] As with the Masters Grand Prix and the ATP Tour World Championships, the Tennis Masters Cup was contested by eight players and teams.
[src:backspin/atp-finals] However, the player or team ranked number eight in the ATP Race world rankings was not guaranteed a spot: if a player or team won one of the year's majors and finished the year ranked from ninth to twentieth, they were included in the Tennis Masters Cup instead.
[src:backspin/atp-finals] If two outside the top eight won majors, the higher-ranked of the two in the world rankings took the final spot.
[src:backspin/atp-finals] This accommodation for major champions continues in the event's current form.
[src:backspin/atp-finals] In 2009, the championship was renamed the "ATP World Tour Finals" and was held at The O2 Arena in London.
[src:backspin/atp-finals] The contract ran through 2013, but was extended multiple times until it was last held there in 2020.
[src:backspin/atp-finals] In 2017 the event was renamed the "ATP Finals".
[src:backspin/atp-finals] In April 2019, the ATP announced that Turin would host the ATP Finals from 2021 to 2025.
[src:backspin/atp-finals] For most of its history, the event has been considered the most important indoor tennis tournament in the world (there were a few exceptions when the event was held outdoors: 1974 in Melbourne & 2003–04 in Houston).
[src:backspin/atp-finals] The indoor atmosphere allows for controlled conditions of play, both in terms of the court surface and the court's illumination.
[src:backspin/atp-finals] In recent years it has been played on indoor hard courts, however, indoor carpet was used in some previous editions.
[src:backspin/atp-finals] On one occasion, when Melbourne hosted the event in 1974, the grass courts of Kooyong Stadium were used; the tournament was staged only 1–2 weeks before the 1975 Australian Open, which was also played on grass.
[src:backspin/atp-finals] Apart from 1974, all tournaments have been on a hard court variant, which has prompted calls from some players (such as Rafael Nadal) to feature a greater variety of surfaces, including clay courts.
[src:backspin/atp-finals] For many years, the doubles event was held as a separate tournament staged the week after the singles competition, but more recently both events have been held together during the same week and in the same venue.
[src:backspin/atp-finals] In 2020, amid the COVID-19 pandemic and in an effort to reduce the number of staff on-site, the ATP introduced live electronic line-calling powered by Hawk-Eye Live.
[src:backspin/atp-finals] Instead of line umpires, the system detects the relevant movements of the player and where the ball bounces on court.
[src:backspin/atp-finals] A pre-recorded voice announces "Out", "Fault", and "Foot fault".
[src:backspin/atp-finals] Video review was also introduced for suspected double bounces, touches, and other reviewable calls.
[src:backspin/atp-finals] The tournament has traditionally been sponsored by the title sponsor of the tour; however, in 1990–2008 the competition was not sponsored, even though the singles portion of the event, as part of the ATP Tour, was sponsored by IBM.
[src:backspin/atp-finals] In 2009, the tournament gained Barclays PLC as its title sponsor.
[src:backspin/atp-finals] Barclays confirmed in 2015 that they would not renew their sponsorship deal once it expires in 2016.
[src:backspin/atp-finals] On 25 May 2017, it was announced that Nitto Denko would be the main sponsor for the tournament through 2020.
[src:backspin/atp-finals] In September 2020, Nitto Denko announced it will extend its title partnership of the ATP Finals for another five years, until 2025.
[src:backspin/atp-finals] In November 2025, Nitto Denko announced it will extend its title partnership of the ATP Finals for another five years, until 2030.
[src:backspin/atp-finals] The eighth spot is reserved for a player or team who won a major in the season and is ranked from eighth to twentieth.
[src:backspin/atp-finals] Goran Ivanišević in 2001, Albert Costa in 2002, Gastón Gaudio in 2004, and Marin Čilić in 2014 are the singles players who have qualified due to their major title despite not ending in the top eight in the ATP race.
[src:backspin/atp-finals] If more than one player or team won a Grand Slam event in the season and are ranked from eighth to twentieth, then whoever is highest-ranked is awarded the eighth spot; whoever is second highest-ranked is made first alternate.
[src:backspin/atp-finals] If there is no player who won a major in the season and is ranked from eighth to twentieth, then the eight spot is awarded to the player ranked eighth.
[src:backspin/atp-finals] Two alternates also attend the ATP Finals.
[src:backspin/atp-finals] If the first alternate has already been selected according to (3) mentioned above, then the second alternate is the highest-ranked player who has not otherwise qualified for the event.
[src:backspin/atp-finals] If both alternate spots are available, they are awarded to the two highest-ranked players who did not otherwise qualify for the event.
[src:backspin/atp-finals] An alternate can replace a player who withdraws before the round-robin stage is over, so long as the player who withdraws still has at least one round-robin match left to play.
[src:backspin/atp-finals] When an alternate enters the competition, his results are considered separately, i.e. the alternate does not inherit the results of the player he is replacing.
[src:backspin/atp-finals] If an alternate's round-robin results qualify him for the semifinals, then he may continue into the single-elimination rounds.
[src:backspin/atp-finals] Unlike other events on the ATP Tour, the ATP Finals is not a straightforward single-elimination tournament.
[src:backspin/atp-finals] The eight players and teams are divided into two groups of four and each play three round-robin matches against the others in their group.
[src:backspin/atp-finals] After the round-robin stage, the top two performers in each group advance to the semifinals in a knock-out stage.
[src:backspin/atp-finals] The two winners of the semifinals play a final to determine the champion.
[src:backspin/atp-finals] In this format, it is theoretically possible to advance to the semifinals with two round-robin losses, but no player in the history of the singles tournament has won the title after losing more than one round-robin match.
[src:backspin/atp-finals] To create the groups, the eight players and teams are seeded according to rank.
[src:backspin/atp-finals] The first and second seeds are placed in Group A and Group B, respectively.
[src:backspin/atp-finals] The remaining seeds are drawn in pairs (third and fourth, fifth and sixth, seventh and eighth); the first of the pair to be drawn goes to Group A and the other to Group B, and so on.
[src:backspin/atp-finals] When calculating tiebreakers, a match that ended in a retirement is counted as a 0–2 sets loss for the retiring player and a 2–0 sets win for their opponent, regardless of the actual score when the retirement occurred.
[src:backspin/atp-finals] When calculating the "Highest % of games won" tiebreaker, a match that ended in a retirement is disregarded.
[src:backspin/atp-finals] ATP Finals is the men's premier indoor event of the season, only in three editions it was played outdoors; 1974, 2003 and 2004.
[src:backspin/atp-finals] At Shanghai, it was played on carpet in 2005 and on hard from 2006 to 2008.
[src:backspin/atp-finals] The 2025 ATP Finals offers the following prize money pool of $15,550,000.
[src:backspin/atp-masters-1000-tournaments-p01] Djokovic also won a record 40 ATP Masters 1000 titles in singles.
[src:backspin/atp-masters-1000-tournaments-p01] Sinner is the fastest player to complete the Golden Masters among all players.
[src:backspin/atp-masters-1000-tournaments-p01] The Bryan brothers also won a record 39 ATP Masters 1000 titles in doubles.
[src:backspin/atp-masters-1000-tournaments-p01] Nestor is the first player to complete the Golden Masters among all players.
[src:backspin/atp-masters-1000-tournaments-p01] The **ATP Masters 1000** tournaments, also known as Masters 1000 or ATP 1000 events, are an annual series of nine tennis tournaments featuring the top-ranked players on the ATP Tour since its inception in 1990.
[src:backspin/atp-masters-1000-tournaments-p01] The ATP 1000 tournaments, sitting below the Grand Slam tournaments and the year-end championships, make up the most coveted trophies on the annual ATP Tour calendar.
[src:backspin/atp-masters-1000-tournaments-p01] In addition to the quadrennial Summer Olympics, they are collectively known as the 'Big Titles'.
[src:backspin/atp-masters-1000-tournaments-p01] Novak Djokovic holds the record for the most ATP 1000 singles titles with 40.
[src:backspin/atp-masters-1000-tournaments-p01] By completing the career set of all nine current ATP 1000 series singles titles in 2018, Djokovic became the first player to achieve the Career Golden Masters.
[src:backspin/atp-masters-1000-tournaments-p01] In 2020, Djokovic completed a second Career Golden Masters.
[src:backspin/atp-masters-1000-tournaments-p01] In 2026, Jannik Sinner became the second, and youngest, player to complete the Career Golden Masters at the age of 24.
[src:backspin/atp-masters-1000-tournaments-p01] In doubles, the Bryan brothers (Bob and Mike) won a record 39 doubles titles as a team.
[src:backspin/atp-masters-1000-tournaments-p01] Daniel Nestor and the Bryan brothers are the only doubles players to achieve the Career Golden Masters.
[src:backspin/atp-masters-1000-tournaments-p01] Out of the five male players who achieved the **Career Golden Masters**, Daniel Nestor is the first player to achieve the feat in 2011 and Sinner is the fastest player to complete the same feat in a record span of 33 months.
[src:backspin/atp-masters-1000-tournaments-p01] The ATP Championship Series (Single Week) was introduced in 1990 with the inception of the ATP Tour by bringing together the nine most prestigious tournaments of the Grand Prix Super Series of the preceding ITF Grand Prix Circuit.
[src:backspin/atp-masters-1000-tournaments-p01] Results in ATP 1000 events earn players more ranking points than regular tournaments but less than Grand Slam events or the year-end ATP Finals.
[src:backspin/atp-masters-1000-tournaments-p01] Up until 2007, most ATP Masters 1000 finals were contested as best-of-five-set matches, but from 2008 all events were decided in best-of-three-set matches.
[src:backspin/atp-masters-1000-tournaments-p01] As part of a shake-up of the tennis circuit in 2009, the Masters Series became the ATP Masters 1000, with the addition of the number 1000 referring to the number of ranking points earned by the winner of each tournament.
[src:backspin/atp-masters-1000-tournaments-p01] Contrary to earlier plans, the number of tournaments was not reduced from nine to eight and the Monte-Carlo Masters remained part of the series although, unlike the other events, it does not have a mandatory player commitment.
[src:backspin/atp-masters-1000-tournaments-p01] The Hamburg Masters event was downgraded to an ATP Tour 500 event.
[src:backspin/atp-masters-1000-tournaments-p01] The Madrid Open moved to May and onto clay courts.
[src:backspin/atp-masters-1000-tournaments-p01] A new tournament in Shanghai replaced the Hamburg Masters and took over Madrid's former October indoor slot.
[src:backspin/atp-masters-1000-tournaments-p01] In 2011, six of the nine 1000 level tournaments were combined ATP and WTA events.
[src:backspin/atp-masters-1000-tournaments-p01] In 2025, all tournaments introduced the Video Review system, starting with the Indian Wells Open.
[src:backspin/atp-masters-1000-tournaments-p01] The following ranking points are as of 2025.
[src:backspin/atp-masters-1000-tournaments-p01] Players with byes losing their first match receive first round points.
[src:backspin/atp-masters-1000-tournaments-p01] Currently, the following nine tournaments are part of the ATP Masters 1000: Canadian Open (alternating yearly between Montreal and Toronto), Italian Open (held in Rome), Indian Wells Open, Miami Open, Monte-Carlo Masters, Madrid Open, Cincinnati Open, Shanghai Masters and Paris Masters.
[src:backspin/atp-masters-1000-tournaments-p01] Since 2009, five of the tournaments have been held on outdoor hard courts, three on clay and one on indoor hard court, whereas from 1990 until 2008 there were two indoor tournaments at the top-9 level.
[src:backspin/atp-masters-1000-tournaments-p01] In 2009, the Shanghai Masters replaced the Madrid Open, which was until then held as an indoor event, in the eighth slot of the year with the Madrid Open switched to clay courts, replacing the Hamburg Open in the spring clay court season.
[src:backspin/atp-masters-1000-tournaments-p01] The Shanghai Masters was designated as an outdoor event despite the facility having a retractable roof and having been used as the indoor venue for the ATP Finals from 2005 until 2008.
[src:backspin/atp-masters-1000-tournaments-p01] Other than Hamburg, the tournaments defunct between 1990 and 2009 were Stockholm (1990–1994) and Stuttgart (1995–2001), which were held as indoor events in the eighth slot.
[src:backspin/atp-masters-1000-tournaments-p01] On October 23, 2025, the ATP announced that a new Masters 1000 tournament (the tenth on the calendar) will be held in Saudi Arabia, likely beginning in 2028, although the specific date remains to be determined.
[src:backspin/atp-masters-1000-tournaments-p01] The placement of the event on the ATP calendar has also not been announced.
[src:backspin/atp-masters-1000-tournaments-p01] The field will be 56 players and the event will be non-mandatory.
[src:backspin/atp-masters-1000-tournaments-p01] This will be the first time the ATP Masters 1000 events number ten in one calendar year.
[src:backspin/atp-masters-1000-tournaments-p01] Madrid Masters was played in the Madrid Arena on an indoor hardcourt from 2002 to 2008.
[src:backspin/atp-masters-1000-tournaments-p01] The men's Canadian Open is held in Montreal in even-numbered years and Toronto in odd-numbered years, alternating with the women's event.
[src:backspin/atp-masters-1000-tournaments-p03] The achievement of winning all of the active nine ATP 1000 Masters tournaments over the course of a player's career.
[src:backspin/atp-tour] The **ATP Tour** (known as **ATP World Tour** between January 2009 and December 2018) is the sole worldwide top-tier tennis tour for men organized by the Association of Tennis Professionals (ATP) founded in 1990 that replaced the earlier dual Grand Prix Circuit and WCT Circuit.
[src:backspin/atp-tour] The second-tier tour is the ATP Challenger Tour and the third-tier is the ITF Men's World Tennis Tour.
[src:backspin/atp-tour] The equivalent women's organisation is the WTA Tour.
[src:backspin/atp-tour] The ATP Tour comprises ATP Masters 1000, ATP 500, and ATP 250 and the United Cup.
[src:backspin/atp-tour] The ATP also oversees the ATP Challenger Tour, a level below the ATP Tour, and the ATP Champions Tour for seniors.
[src:backspin/atp-tour] The Grand Slam tournaments, the Olympic tennis tournament, the Davis Cup, and the entry-level ITF World Tennis Tour do not fall under the purview of the ATP, but are overseen by the International Tennis Federation (ITF) instead and the International Olympic Committee (IOC) for the Olympics.
[src:backspin/atp-tour] In these events, however, ATP ranking points are awarded, with the exception of the Olympics.
[src:backspin/atp-tour] Players and doubles teams with the most ranking points (collected during the calendar year) play in the season-ending ATP Finals, which, from 2000–2008, was run jointly with the ITF.
[src:backspin/atp-tour] The top eight 20-and-under players may compete in the season-ending Next Generation ATP Finals if they do not qualify for the ATP Finals.
[src:backspin/atp-tour] ATP publishes weekly rankings of professional players.
[src:backspin/backspin] In sports, **backspin** or **underspin** refers to the reverse rotation of a ball, in relation to the ball's trajectory, that is imparted on the ball by a **slice** or **chop** shot.
[src:backspin/backspin] Backspin generates an upward force that lifts the ball (see Magnus effect).
[src:backspin/backspin] While a normal hit bounces well forward as well as up, backspin shots bounce higher and less forward.
[src:backspin/backspin] In racket sports, the higher bounce imparted by backspin may make a receiver who has prepared for a different shot miss or mis-hit the ball when swinging.
[src:backspin/backspin] A backspin shot is also useful for defensive shots because a backspin shot takes longer to travel to the opponent, giving the defender more time to get back into position.
[src:backspin/backspin] Also, because backspin shots tend to bounce less far forward once they reach the opposite court, they may be more difficult to attack.
[src:backspin/backspin] This is especially important in table tennis because one must wait for the ball to bounce before hitting it, whereas in tennis the opponent may volley the ball.
[src:backspin/backspin] In golf, a well-struck shot will result in a large amount of backspin that will carry the ball higher into the air and further.
[src:backspin/backspin] Backspin will also help with distance control and, if there is enough backspin, the ball will "check" if it lands on the putting surface, and sometimes even creep backwards (in the opposite direction that the ball was flying) upon landing.
